  "text": "The Firefox TLS connection chain from the networking layer to the crypto layer proceeds as follows:\n\n**Hop 1 — `netwerk/protocol/http/nsHttpConnection.cpp` (`nsHttpConnection`)**\nThe `nsHttpConnection` class in `netwerk/protocol/http/nsHttpConnection.cpp` is the HTTP/1.x connection object. When a connection is established to an HTTPS server, `nsHttpConnection::IsAlive()` calls `mTlsHandshaker->SetupSSL()`. The `TlsHandshaker` class (implemented in `netwerk/protocol/http/TlsHandshaker.cpp`) orchestrates TLS setup: `TlsHandshaker::SetupSSL()` checks whether the first hop requires SSL (`mConnInfo->FirstHopSSL()`), then calls `TlsHandshaker::InitSSLParams()` which retrieves the `nsITLSSocketControl` interface and calls `ssl->ProxyStartSSL()` and `ssl->SetHandshakeCallbackListener()` to configure ALPN/NPN protocol negotiation.\n\n**Hop 2 — `security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.h` / `nsNSSIOLayer.cpp` (`nsSSLIOLayerHelpers`)**\nThe `nsSSLIOLayerHelpers` class is declared in `security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.h` (not in `netwerk/socket/` as the task description suggests — it lives in the PSM/security layer). This class manages the NSPR I/O layer identity (`nsSSLIOLayerIdentity`, `nsSSLPlaintextLayerIdentity`) and TLS intolerance tracking. The `nsSSLSocketProvider` (in `security/manager/ssl/nsSSLSocketProvider.cpp`) implements `nsISocketProvider` and bridges Necko's socket layer to NSS by calling `nsSSLIOLayerNewSocket()` and `nsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket()` — both defined in `nsNSSIOLayer.cpp`.\n\n**Hop 3 — `security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.cpp` (`nsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket` / `nsSSLIOLayerNewSocket`)**\n`nsNSSIOLayer.cpp` implements the NSS I/O layer integration. `nsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket()` pushes an NSS SSL NSPR layer onto an existing NSPR file descriptor, creating an `NSSSocketControl` object that wraps the NSS `PRFileDesc*`. This is where the Necko socket transport is connected to the NSS TLS state machine. The file includes NSS headers (`ssl.h`, `sslerr.h`, `sslexp.h`, `sslproto.h`) and calls NSS APIs to configure cipher suites, protocol versions, and certificate verification callbacks.\n\n**Hop 4 — `security/nss/lib/ssl/sslsecur.c` and `security/nss/lib/ssl/ssl3con.c`**\nThe actual TLS handshake is performed in NSS. `sslsecur.c` contains `ssl_Do1stHandshake()` — the main handshake driver that loops calling `ss->handshake(ss)` until the handshake completes — and `SSL_ForceHandshake()` which is the public API entry point. `ssl3con.c` (the SSL3/TLS protocol implementation) contains `ssl3_SendClientHello()` which sends the TLS ClientHello message initiating the handshake, and `ssl3_HandleServerHelloDone()` which processes the server's response. Together these two files implement the complete TLS 1.2/1.3 handshake state machine."
}

